passages.text: 2QF26 reveals billings lufpiness, but management flags better visibility and growing confidence that prompted updated billings guide for 2HF26E

Despite lumpiness of billings in the quarter that appears to be weighing on VEEV stock in the aftermarket trading, management flagged increased confidence in the back- end heavy seasonality, which prompted an increase in the annual guidance - a target that provides better indication of the health of demand. Positively, there have been no changes to pipeline or customer behavior despite continued macro uncertainty and no delays in decisions or timing of deals from OBBB. Agentic AI monetization was the center of discussion with CEO flagging substantial opportunity from integration with partner AI agents, while resolution of IQVIA lawsuit unlocks new areas of integrations that are highly demanded by customers.

- Headline numbers ahead. VEEV reported 2Q26 (qtr ending July 2025) with total revenue/adj EBIT of \(\sim\) 3789M/353M, compared to JPM estimates of \(\$ 766M/\) 337M and Street estimates of \(\$ 768M/336M\)

- **Ornery Mood:** 1) We liked that 2QF26 subscription revenue came in 1.5% ahead of company guide, however note that growth of the commercial portion of the subscription decelerated to 13% yoy (vs. 17% yoy in prior quarter partially explained by slightly tougher base) - usage based revenue continues to result in lumpiness in the Crossix business, however management remains upbeat taking market share and expanding product footprint; 2) Subscription gross margin was down 0.3pp yoy and 1.9pp QoQ to 86.2% - this was related to additional network related costs and additionally near-term margins will be impacted by the transition to Vault CRM as customers initially run both new and legacy CRM systems; 3) Even though growth of normalized billings in 2QF26 decelerated to 10% yoy (vs. 16% yoy in 1QF26), management suggested that annual performance provides a better look and raised FY26E billings outlook by \(\$ 35M\) to \(\$ 3.355B\) (the raise included \(\$ 10M\) of incremental FX tailwind - now \(\$ 30M\) for the year; it also incorporated incremental \(\$ 2M\) tailwind from billing term changes - now \(\$ 25M\)); management outlook envisages an \(\mathbb{E}\mathbb{N}\) larger billings outlook for the back half of fiscal 2026E; 4) While management raised FY26E operating cash flow by \(\$ 120M\) , \(\$ 135M\) of that increase came from OBBB, which implies a \(\$ 15M\) cut in the guide partially explained by \(\$ 30M\) cost related to IQVIA settlement; 5) Despite reporting one more CRM customer loss to Salesforce among top-20 pharma players, VEEV reported 2 additional commitments in the reported quarter, 1 commitment in August and another 2 verbal commitments, bringing the total to 9 customers among top-20 players.

- **Bright Spots:** 1) Services revenue beat consensus by almost 10% coming in at \(\sim\) \(130M\); commercial solutions portion grew 6% yoy (having declined for five prior straight quarters), while R&D solutions revenue growth accelerated to 18% yoy (vs. 15% yoy in prior quarter); CFO flagged projects going faster than initially expected in the quarter that drove the outperformance; 2) Despite

Veeva has a substantial addressable market of \(\sim\) 20B,and the company has seen robust revenue growth of \(20\%\) over the past five years, outpacing Life Sciences industry growth of midsingle digits. Longer term, VEEV anticipates achieving \$6B in annualized revenue by 2030 with north of \(35\%\) EBIT margins, but near-term challenges exist in the marketplace due to macro headwinds. While we find it difficult to bottom- up build to the company's underlying growth rates, we ultimately see MSD industry growth, a competitively differentiated platformapproach, and \(\sim 14\%\) penetration in the TAM as good barometers for underlying support of longer- term targets.

We are establishing a Dec- 26 PT of \$290/sh (vs. a Dec- 25 PT of \$274/sh previously). We forecast all three financial statements in detail through VEEV's FY28 (ending Jan- 2028). We apply a \(10\%\) WACC and forecast a \(2\%\) terminal growth rate. At our Dec 2026 PT of \$290/sh, VEEV would trade at 26x EV/EBITDA in Calendar Year 2026E.

continued macro uncertainty, management has not seen any material change in buying behaviour or pipeline; 3) VEEV has not yet seen any material impact on projects, decisions or timing of deals from OBBB. Vault CRM migration progressing well with the platform now having 100 live customers, up from 80 in 1Q. Management still believes the company is on track to reach \(\sim 200\) live customers by next year and \(\frac{2}{3}\) of customers over the next 18 months. 5) Agentic AI was the key focus on today's earnings call and sell- side callback, with management sounding highly optimistic around potential monetization opportunities and integration with partner AI agents that will drive better industry efficiency and customer success.

- Resolution of IQVIA lawsuit is solving urgent challenges as IQVIA was not a CRO partner (eliminating friction for the customers) and getting products ahead of previous deadlines. Customers wanted to use business consulting but could not use commercial analytics of VEEV - day 1 of the agreement - so near-term eliminating this customer frustration. Additionally, VEEV sees unlocking future potential for monetization of its solutions - new areas of innovation that VEEV has not considered in the past as they did not communicate with IQVIA on those opportunities to provide new integrations for customers. While timeframe remains uncertain for new potential opportunities, VEEV sees this as a significant partnership.

- JPM Reaction: Reiterate Neutral, while establishing our Dec-26 PT of \(\) 290\(/sh. We maintain our Neutral rating on VEEV relative to our coverage universe, while establishing a Dec-26 PT of\) \ \(290 / sh\) (vs. a Dec-25 PT of \(\) 274 / sh\(previously). At our PT, VEEV would trade at 26x EV/EBITDA in 2026E.
